\description{
Production helper for the \verb{&str} zero-copy argument-borrow path (#664).

On the main-thread default, \verb{#[miniextendr]} lowers a \verb{&str} argument to a \emph{direct} zero-copy borrow over R's CHARSXP pool (no owning-\code{String} copy). This fn just measures the borrow and echoes it back so the round-trip can be asserted from the GC driver below.

Convert an R vector to an ALTREP-backed vector by materializing then re-wrapping. Dispatches on \code{type_of()}: INTSXP, REALSXP, STRSXP.

Exercise \code{DataFrame::group_by} + \code{GroupedDataFrame::frames} SEXP handling under GC pressure.

\code{GroupedDataFrame} holds the source frame's SEXP across the per-group \code{select_rows} allocations, and each yielded sub-frame is unprotected until the \code{NamedDataFrameListBuilder} push roots it — the two SEXP-across- allocations paths this fixture drives. Synthesizes a 60-row frame with a character key (incl. NAs) internally.

No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg fixture sweep.

Drive every \code{ser.rs} serializer state machine under GC pressure.

The serializers hold intermediate element SEXPs in \verb{Vec<SEXP>} fields across the allocations performed by subsequent \verb{serialize_*} calls — the canonical "SEXP storage across allocations" shape. This fixture exercises \code{SeqSerializer} (homogeneous + heterogeneous), \code{MapSerializer}, \code{StructSerializer}, \code{TupleVariantSerializer}, \code{StructVariantSerializer}, and the \code{make_tagged_list} newtype-variant path in one nested value.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Drive the zero-copy \verb{&str} argument borrow under GC pressure (#664).

\verb{#[miniextendr] fn(s: &str)} now borrows R's CHARSXP data directly instead of copying into a \code{String} first. The borrow is sound because the argument SEXP is a live wrapper parameter for the whole \code{with_r_unwind_protect} call, and its lifetime is tied to that scope (storing it past the call is a borrow-check error). This fixture synthesises a STRSXP internally, takes a zero-copy \verb{&str} view over each element exactly as the generated wrapper does, and verifies the bytes survive \code{gctorture(TRUE)} — a corrupted/freed borrow would surface as wrong contents rather than a clean read.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Exercise \code{array_to_sexp} PROTECT discipline for integer, float, and boolean TOML arrays under GC pressure.

Constructs \code{TomlValue::Array} values covering the four homogeneous branches of \code{array_to_sexp} and converts each to SEXP via \code{IntoR}, verifying that the \code{OwnedProtect} guards keep each allocation live across the fill loop. No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg fixture sweep.

Exercise \code{dataframe_to_vec_borrowed} PROTECT discipline under GC pressure.

Synthesises 10 rows via \code{vec_to_dataframe}, then deserialises through \code{dataframe_to_vec_borrowed} and reads back via the \verb{BorrowedRows<'_, T>} handle. Verifies the internal \code{OwnedProtect} keeps the source SEXP rooted while we read each row.

No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg sweep.

Exercise map-field \verb{Vec<Vec<K>>} / \verb{Vec<Vec<V>>} column codegen under GC pressure.

Synthesizes realistic \code{HashMapEvent} and \code{BTreeMapEvent} rows and drives both \code{to_dataframe} (align) and \code{to_dataframe_split} (per-variant partition) paths. Verifies that the \code{ProtectScope::protect_raw} calls in the generated map-column code keep each inner \verb{Vec<K>} / \verb{Vec<V>} SEXP live across the subsequent \code{into_sexp()} call for the parallel column.

Exercise the factor-label path through \code{dataframe_to_vec} under GC pressure.

The factor branch in \code{CellDeserializer::deserialize_str/string/char/any} reads \code{levels} (via \code{Rf_getAttrib}) and dereferences \code{STRING_ELT} on the levels SEXP — a path that crosses a GC barrier. This fixture synthesises a one-column factor data.frame internally, then runs \code{dataframe_to_vec} to reconstruct \verb{Vec<Row \{ status: String \}>}. The intermediate factor + data.frame SEXPs are protected via \code{OwnedProtect}; the deserialiser must keep them rooted across the per-row label lookups.

No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg sweep.

Exercise the new \code{ProtectScope} FFI wrapper methods under GC pressure.

Chains at least 6 of the new wrappers with intermediate allocations between each call to ensure GC pressure between steps: - \code{alloc_lang} (LANGSXP node) - \code{cons} / \code{lcons} (pairlist / language cons cells) - \code{lengthgets} (resize a vector) - \code{alloc_array} (n-dimensional array with protected dims INTSXP) - \code{mkchar_len_ce} + \code{mkchar_ce} (CHARSXP with specified encoding)

Each step forces a fresh allocation, so \code{gctorture(TRUE)} exercises the protection of each intermediate result. Returns a trivial integer count (the number of operations performed) so the testthat assertion is meaningful.

No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg fixture sweep.

Exercise \code{make_rust_condition_value_with_data} under GC pressure.

The condition-data path builds a fresh VECSXP + names STRSXP and materialises each \code{ConditionDataValue} field one at a time, rooting every intermediate into the protected data list before the next allocation — the canonical "SEXP storage across allocations" shape (#430). This fixture drives the production code path directly with all eight supported value types (scalar + vector × i32/f64/bool/String) and reads every field back to verify integrity.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Exercise \code{JiffZonedVec} ALTREP construction and element access under GC pressure.

Constructs a single-timezone \code{JiffZonedVec} with several \code{America/New_York} timestamps, converts it to an SEXP via \code{into_sexp}, and forces element access to verify that both the \code{into_sexp_altrep} allocation and the \code{set_posixct_tz} PROTECT path are GC-safe.

No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg fixture sweep.

Drive \verb{RCow<T>}'s borrowed (zero-copy) and owned (copy-on-write) \code{IntoR} paths under GC pressure.

Companion to \code{gc_stress_cow_subslice_roundtrip} (#880). \code{RCow} is the safe zero-copy round-trip type: its borrowed arm carries the source SEXP, so \code{IntoR} hands that SEXP straight back with no \verb{data_ptr − header} probe. This fixture confirms (a) the borrowed round-trip returns the \emph{same} SEXP, and (b) \code{to_mut()} forces a fresh, value-correct copy — both without corruption under \code{gctorture(TRUE)}.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Exercise \code{vec_to_dataframe_split(Collated)} under GC pressure. Drives the \code{TaggedVariantRow} / \code{MapForwarder} collation path through the schema-union machinery in \code{vec_to_dataframe}.

Exercise \code{vec_to_dataframe_split(PerVariantListWithTag)} under GC pressure. The tag-column prepend allocates a per-partition STRSXP that must be protected through the \code{prepend_column} VECSXP reshuffle.

Exercise \code{RDataFrameBuilder} parallel column-fill under GC pressure.

Builds a heterogeneous data.frame (numeric \code{x}, integer \code{y}, character \code{label} with interspersed \code{NA}) via the parallel builder, across two column shapes:
\enumerate{
\item A balanced 3-column frame (\code{x}/\code{y}/\code{label}). 2. A \strong{few-long-columns} frame (one numeric + one character, both spanning enough rows to split into many row-range chunks) — the shape the flattened \verb{(column, row-range)} work-list targets, and the one most likely to expose a PROTECT-window bug because the parallel pass touches many disjoint slices of the same column buffers.
}

The builder allocates each column SEXP serially, holds them protected across subsequent column / names / row.names / class allocations, and assembles the parent \code{VECSXP}. This is exactly the SEXP-across-allocation path that needs a gctorture pass. No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture sweep.

Drive the \code{RCall} builder + eval path under GC pressure. The builder holds its argument SEXPs in a \verb{Vec<(Option<CString>, SEXP)>} while later arguments and the \code{build()} cons-chain allocate — exactly the SEXP-storage-across-allocations shape #430 requires a no-arg fixture for. Arguments are protected here per the builder's contract (caller keeps args reachable); the fixture verifies \code{build()}/\code{eval()}'s internal PROTECT discipline. Returns \code{paste("alpha", "beta", sep = "-")}, i.e. "alpha-beta".

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Build a \verb{Vec<ExternalPtr<T>>} the \emph{naive} way and read every handle back through \code{R_ExternalPtrAddr}, under GC pressure.

This is the regression fixture for #836: \code{ExternalPtr::new} roots its \code{EXTPTRSXP} via \code{R_PreserveObject} for the handle's whole Rust lifetime, so the per-element allocation in \verb{.map(ExternalPtr::new).collect()} cannot collect the earlier handles already sitting in the \code{Vec}. Pre-#836 this reliably corrupted under \code{gctorture(TRUE)}; the \verb{#827} fixtures had to root each handle manually with a \code{ProtectScope}.

The readback re-wraps via \code{wrap_sexp} (the \emph{honest} check — it inspects \code{R_ExternalPtrAddr}), not the cached \verb{*mut T} \code{Deref}, which would read freed memory and silently "pass". The throwaway-batch loop also drives the new \code{Drop} → \code{R_ReleaseObject} path while the kept handles are still live.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Exercise the map-column enum reader under GC pressure.

