A normal \code{run_on_worker} round-trip that also routes through \code{with_r_thread}, returning a value the R side can assert on.

This is the \emph{second} job in the #931 worker-re-usability test: the test first triggers an R longjmp through a worker job via \code{gc_stress_with_r_thread_stop} (which never returns — it resumes the original \code{Rf_error} straight to R's top level, see #733 / PR #930), catches that error at top level, then calls this fixture. If the worker thread were left poisoned by the unwind (its \code{recv()} loop not re-armed, thread-locals not cleared, a wedged channel), this second dispatch would hang, panic, or return the wrong value.

Shape: the fn returns \code{SEXP}, so the macro picks the \strong{MainThread} strategy — the body is the thread that drives \code{dispatch_to_worker}'s event loop. It dispatches a closure to the worker, which routes a trivial computation back to the main thread via \code{with_r_thread}, then returns the sum. We assert the arithmetic is correct so a partially-corrupted worker (stale thread-local channels from the prior aborted job) surfaces as a wrong answer rather than a silent pass.

No arguments — also picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430): it holds no SEXPs across allocations itself, but exercising the worker dispatch under GC pressure is cheap insurance.

