Drive an \strong{R error raised inside a \code{with_r_thread} closure from a \code{run_on_worker} job} end-to-end, so the \code{cleanup_handler} / \code{R_ContinueUnwind} path in \code{worker.rs} (the worker-job R-longjmp branch) is exercised under R's normal top-level error handler.

This is the #733 follow-up to #731's \code{worker_channel_stress.rs} cargo suite. That cargo path \strong{cannot} safely cover this case: the cargo-test R embedding (\code{r_test_utils.rs}) runs raw FFI jobs in a \code{for} loop with no R top-level handler, so \code{R_ContinueUnwind(token)} would resume an unwind with nowhere to land — a likely segfault rather than a clean test. Inside an rpkg testthat run R's normal error handler is in place, so the resumed unwind lands at the top level and the framework re-raises it as a tagged condition.

Shape (entirely synthesised internally so it's callable with no args, per the no-arg gctorture-fixture convention, #430):
\enumerate{
\item The fn returns \code{SEXP}, so the macro picks the \strong{MainThread} strategy: the body runs on R's main thread and is the thread that drives \code{dispatch_to_worker}'s event loop (no re-entrant \code{run_on_worker}). 2. \code{run_on_worker} moves the closure onto the worker thread. 3. From the worker, \code{with_r_thread} routes back to the main thread, which calls \code{Rf_error_unchecked} — an R error. R \code{R_UnwindProtect}'s \code{cleanup_handler} fires, sends \code{Err(msg)} to the worker so it can't deadlock on \code{response_rx.recv()}, then \code{R_ContinueUnwind}s the longjmp. (\verb{_unchecked} is valid here: we're inside a \code{with_r_thread} callback — MXL301-permitted context.) 4. \code{R_ContinueUnwind} resumes the \emph{original} R \code{Rf_error} longjmp on the main thread, which lands directly at R's top level. So the surfaced condition is a \strong{bare \code{simpleError}} carrying the original message — the macro's tagged-condition transport (\code{rust_error}) is bypassed entirely, and the \code{run_on_worker} call below \strong{never returns} on this path. This answers the #733 open question on how the condition is layered. The \code{match} below is therefore a defensive guard, not the live path.
}

The companion testthat test (\code{test-worker-longjmp.R}) asserts that the call errors and that the condition is a \code{simpleError} carrying the original message (and explicitly NOT a \code{rust_error}). Existing \code{test-worker.R} coverage of the same raw-\code{Rf_error} shape only matched the message text.

