Exercise \code{NamedDataFrameListBuilder} SEXP protection under GC pressure.

Pushes two \code{DataFrame}s (synthesised internally via \code{vec_to_dataframe}) into a \code{NamedDataFrameListBuilder} and calls \code{build()}.  Each \code{push} stores the input SEXP in an internal \verb{Vec<SEXP>} (protected by the builder's \code{ProtectScope}), making this the canonical gctorture coverage for the SEXP-storage-across-allocations path in the builder.

No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg fixture sweep.

Exercise \verb{Vec<Option<collection>>} conversions under GC pressure.

Allocates \verb{Vec<Option<Vec<i32>>>}, \verb{Vec<Option<HashSet<String>>>}, and \verb{Vec<Option<BTreeSet<i32>>>} and converts each to SEXP, verifying that the \code{OwnedProtect} in \code{vec_option_of_into_r_to_list} keeps the outer list live across inner \code{into_sexp()} calls.

Exercise the \verb{AsNamedList<Vec<(String, V)>>} deferred-conversion path under GC pressure.

\code{AsNamedList::into_sexp} builds each value's \code{SEXP} and hands the lot to \code{List::from_raw_pairs}. Before #1030 the values were collected unprotected (\verb{.map(|(k, v)| (k, v.into_sexp())).collect()}), so an earlier value sat unrooted while a later value's \code{into_sexp()} allocated — a use-after-free under \code{gctorture(TRUE)}. The fix wraps each \code{v.into_sexp()} in \code{ProtectScope::protect_raw} so every sibling stays rooted across the next allocation.

This fixture drives a \emph{typed} heterogeneous list (the GC-safe replacement for the old raw-\code{SEXP}-value fixture): a mix of character, integer and double scalar values (each scalar allocation can fire GC), repeated enough times that \code{from_raw_pairs}'s own \code{charsxp}/\code{SET_VECTOR_ELT} allocations interleave with the value builds. Honest readback: every element is read back through \code{VECTOR_ELT} and compared, so a collected value would surface as a wrong/garbage element rather than silently passing.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Round-trip a \code{Cow::Borrowed} \emph{sub-slice} of an R-backed vector through \code{IntoR}, exercising the \verb{Cow<[T]>::into_sexp} copy path under GC pressure.

Regression guard for #880. A borrowed sub-slice (\verb{&full[2..]}) points into the \emph{middle} of an R vector: \code{slice.as_ptr()} is offset from the SEXP data start, so the old speculative \code{try_recover_r_sexp} probe (\verb{data_ptr − header}) would read provenance-free memory off the front of the vector and could false-positive as a "recovered SEXP" — the same class of hazard #867 fixed for Arrow, but for a bare \verb{&[T]} that carries no metadata to gate on. The fix removes the probe and always copies; this fixture proves the copy round-trips the correct sliced values without crashing or returning a bogus SEXP.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Exercise \code{dispatch_to_dataframes} PROTECT discipline under GC pressure.

Synthesises a mixed Result-iterator (every third row is an Err with a distinct payload shape) and runs it through the streaming two-builder path. Each builder's \code{ProtectScope} plus the assembling \code{NamedDataFrameListBuilder} need to keep every protected SEXP live.

No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg sweep.

Exercise \code{dataframe_to_vec} nested-struct un-flattening under GC pressure.

Synthesizes 10 rows of a nested \verb{Person \{ name, address: Address \{ city, zip \} \}} struct via \code{vec_to_dataframe}, then reconstructs them via \code{dataframe_to_vec} using the single-underscore prefix-matching path. Returns the row count. No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture no-arg sweep.

Materialize a \code{RecordBatch} whose columns are \emph{sliced views} of R-backed Arrow buffers, exercising \code{RecordBatch::into_sexp} → \code{arrow_array_to_sexp} → the per-array zero-copy SEXP-recovery path under GC pressure.

Regression fixture for #867. \code{test_df_subquery} segfaulted on the strict glibc Linux runner because DataFusion's contiguous-run filter optimization returns a \emph{slice} of the R-backed input column: \verb{values().as_ptr()} then points into the middle of the R vector, and the speculative \code{try_recover_r_sexp} probe (which subtracts the SEXPREC header offset) read off into unrelated memory and false-positived as a "recovered SEXP". The crash was heap-layout-dependent — deterministic on the strict runner, silent elsewhere — so a no-arg fixture is the only portable guard.

This fixture builds R-backed \code{Int32Array}/\code{Float64Array} columns, slices them (offset > 0, the exact filter-optimization shape), assembles a \code{RecordBatch}, and drives the production materialization. It then verifies the resulting data.frame holds the correct values — a false-positive recovery would yield wrong values or corrupt memory rather than copying.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

Exercise \code{DataFrame::builder} on the \strong{non-rayon} (serial) fill path under GC pressure.

rpkg compiles with \code{rayon} \strong{off} by default, so this fixture drives the serial fill branch of \code{RDataFrameBuilder::build} (#1055) — proving the builder surface is reachable and correct without the \code{rayon} feature. It uses the public \code{DataFrame::builder(nrow)} entry point (no \code{rayon_bridge} import), then materializes every column under a single protect scope so any stale/freed column surfaces. The builder allocates each column SEXP serially and holds it protected across the subsequent column / names / row.names / class allocations — the SEXP-across-allocation path that needs a gctorture pass. No arguments — suitable for the fast gctorture sweep.

Build an R \code{list()} of external pointers via \code{ExternalPtr::collect_into_r_list} under GC pressure, then read every element back through \code{R_ExternalPtrAddr}.

Regression fixture for the destination-rooting bulk builder — the safe, no-pool alternative to a hot \verb{Vec<ExternalPtr>} build. \code{collect_into_r_list} creates each \code{EXTPTRSXP} \emph{directly into the protected result list}, so every earlier element stays rooted by the list while later elements allocate. Under \code{gctorture(TRUE)} each per-element allocation forces a full GC; if the list did not root the elements (a missing \code{Rf_protect} or \code{SET_VECTOR_ELT}), the earlier ones would be collected and the readback would see a null \code{R_ExternalPtrAddr}.

The readback is allocation-free (\code{VECTOR_ELT} + \code{R_ExternalPtrAddr} are pointer reads), so no GC can fire between the build and the reads — the returned (caller-rooted-by-contract) list stays live on the Rust stack without us touching R's protect stack off the main thread.

No arguments — picked up by the fast \code{gctorture(TRUE)} no-arg sweep (#430).

